<paragraph blockId="38.[159,1116,940,1477]" pageId="38" pageNumber="2995">
<emphasis box="[199,271,1195,1219]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="2995">Notes.</emphasis>
(1) 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Decaisne" authorityYear="1842" box="[330,523,1195,1219]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Udoteaceae" genus="Udotea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Bryopsidales" pageId="38" pageNumber="2995" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="palmetta">
<emphasis box="[330,523,1195,1219]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="2995">Udotea palmetta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="A. Gepp and E. Gepp. Anatomically" authorityName="A. Gepp and E. Gepp. Anatomically" authorityYear="1908" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Bryopsidaceae" genus="Bryopsis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Bryopsidales" pageId="38" pageNumber="2995" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="indica">
<emphasis box="[965,1073,1195,1219]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="2995">U. indica</emphasis>
A. Gepp and E. Gepp. Anatomically
</taxonomicName>
they are distinguished by the morphology of the lateral appendages of the flabellum filaments. These are blunt in the latter and acute in the former. In 
<taxonomicName box="[503,645,1292,1316]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Udoteaceae" genus="Udotea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Bryopsidales" pageId="38" pageNumber="2995" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="orientalis">
<emphasis box="[503,645,1292,1316]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="2995">U. orientalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
these filaments have no appendages at all. (2) One collection (
<accessionNumber box="[444,585,1324,1348]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/protein/HEC14817" pageId="38" pageNumber="2995">HEC 14817</accessionNumber>
) is fertile and carries numerous dark green gametocysts in the middle (
<figureCitation box="[465,562,1356,1380]" captionStart="FIGS" captionStartId="27.[154,170,1086,1108]" captionTargetBox="[160,1106,175,1042]" captionTargetId="figure-140@27.[154,1111,170,1048]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGS 19–24. Chlorophyta. (19) Caulerpa nummularia, proliferating from primary, peltate assimilator (HEC 14609 p.p.). (20) Rhipidosiphon javensis (HEC 14763). (21) Udotea sp. (HEC 14759). (22–24) Udotea palmetta (HEC 14817): (22) general morphology of large, fertile specimen; (23) gametangia growing from the blade surface; (24) gametangia growing from the blade margin. Scale bars: 2 mm (19, 20); 1 cm (21, 22); 1 mm (23); 500 mm (24)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5251853" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5251853/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="2995">figure 23</figureCitation>
) and marginal (
<figureCitation box="[742,839,1356,1380]" captionStart="FIGS" captionStartId="27.[154,170,1086,1108]" captionTargetBox="[160,1106,175,1042]" captionTargetId="figure-140@27.[154,1111,170,1048]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGS 19–24. Chlorophyta. (19) Caulerpa nummularia, proliferating from primary, peltate assimilator (HEC 14609 p.p.). (20) Rhipidosiphon javensis (HEC 14763). (21) Udotea sp. (HEC 14759). (22–24) Udotea palmetta (HEC 14817): (22) general morphology of large, fertile specimen; (23) gametangia growing from the blade surface; (24) gametangia growing from the blade margin. Scale bars: 2 mm (19, 20); 1 cm (21, 22); 1 mm (23); 500 mm (24)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5251853" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5251853/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="2995">figure 24</figureCitation>
) parts of the whitish flabellum. (3) The fully grown specimens are very large when compared to those from 
<collectingCountry box="[159,233,1421,1445]" name="Kenya" pageId="38" pageNumber="2995">Kenya</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[296,403,1421,1445]" name="Tanzania" pageId="38" pageNumber="2995">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
, but they still agree with the original description. The stipe is up to 
<quantity box="[227,278,1453,1477]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="2995" unit="cm" value="4.0">4 cm</quantity>
long, the flabellum 10 (but up to 15) cm long and 
<quantity box="[846,909,1453,1477]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="38" pageNumber="2995" unit="cm" value="14.0">14 cm</quantity>
broad.
</paragraph>
